His interests also extended to history. Working diligently in archives and libraries, and taking advantage of archaeological findings, he published his Fasti consulares (1550), which chronicles the history of Rome, and his De regno Italiae (1580), which traces the development of the Italian kingdom from the invasion of the Lombards in 568 to the end of the thirteenth century. The quantity and significance of his historical writings have shifted attention away from his contributions in philology and literary criticism‚ in general, and from his definition of dialogue, in particular.
